00:01:33.140 --> 00:01:36.570
- So fashion is
supposed to be a form

00:01:36.570 --> 00:01:39.990
of nonverbal communication,
which means that you all

00:01:39.990 --> 00:01:42.990
ought to be able to
read my clothing,

00:01:42.990 --> 00:01:45.720
if not the clothing
of 500 years ago.

00:01:45.720 --> 00:01:46.980
So I'd like to start--

00:01:46.980 --> 00:01:49.230
where's the
microphone out there?

00:01:49.230 --> 00:01:50.670
If someone can
get the microphone

00:01:50.670 --> 00:01:52.680
or just stand up
and project, I'd

00:01:52.680 --> 00:01:57.090
like you to tell me what you
can tell about me by what I'm

00:01:57.090 --> 00:02:00.360
wearing, what I look like,
and how I might differ

00:02:00.360 --> 00:02:04.170
from people of 500 years ago.

00:02:04.170 --> 00:02:05.610
- You're a New Yorker.

00:02:05.610 --> 00:02:08.850
- Because I'm wearing black,
he says I'm a New Yorker.

00:02:08.850 --> 00:02:09.810
Well, it's true.

00:02:09.810 --> 00:02:12.912
New Yorkers tend to wear black
but only in some neighborhoods.

00:02:12.912 --> 00:02:14.370
I tell you, on the
Upper East Side,

00:02:14.370 --> 00:02:17.600
those rich ladies
don't wear black.

00:02:17.600 --> 00:02:18.100
What else?

00:02:18.100 --> 00:02:19.740
- [INAUDIBLE] a businesswoman.

00:02:19.740 --> 00:02:22.300
- Businesswoman-- eh, not quite.

00:02:22.300 --> 00:02:24.880
I'm an administrator,
which means I'm not loved.

00:02:24.880 --> 00:02:26.650
But I'm not exactly business.

00:02:26.650 --> 00:02:28.240
I'm not raking in the money.

00:02:28.240 --> 00:02:29.670
How did you read
business, though?

00:02:29.670 --> 00:02:30.340
- The suit.

00:02:30.340 --> 00:02:31.020
- The suit.

00:02:31.020 --> 00:02:32.350
The suit, exactly.

00:02:32.350 --> 00:02:34.450
OK, so it reads like business.

00:02:34.450 --> 00:02:37.330
That's right, like that
Victorian cartoon where

00:02:37.330 --> 00:02:39.280
the man says, I mean business.

00:02:39.280 --> 00:02:40.845
- Have you taken dance?

00:02:40.845 --> 00:02:41.470
- Say it again.

00:02:41.470 --> 00:02:43.540
- Have you taken dance?

00:02:43.540 --> 00:02:46.060
- I took it very briefly,
although I'm really

00:02:46.060 --> 00:02:48.910
a horseback-riding
girl, not a ballet girl.

00:02:48.910 --> 00:02:51.130
- [INAUDIBLE]

00:02:51.130 --> 00:02:51.756
- Yes.

00:02:51.756 --> 00:02:54.130
- Great sneakers,
probably loves shoes.

00:02:54.130 --> 00:02:55.240
- I do love shoes.

00:02:55.240 --> 00:02:55.780
I do.

00:02:55.780 --> 00:02:58.480
But whereas I used to be called
the high-heels historian,

00:02:58.480 --> 00:03:01.360
now I'm in sneakers
90% of the time.

00:03:01.360 --> 00:03:04.840
I was in the gym, this
public gym for poor people.

00:03:04.840 --> 00:03:07.270
And this guy lifting
400 pounds stops,

00:03:07.270 --> 00:03:09.870
and he looks at this pair
of sneakers, and he goes,

00:03:09.870 --> 00:03:12.010
are those [INAUDIBLE] sneakers?

00:03:12.010 --> 00:03:14.110
And I said in my
snobbyist voice,

00:03:14.110 --> 00:03:17.230
why, yes, these are
[INAUDIBLE] sneakers.

00:03:17.230 --> 00:03:19.690
And he said, yeah, I like
the crinkle leather version

00:03:19.690 --> 00:03:21.460
better--

00:03:21.460 --> 00:03:23.097
put me in my place.

00:03:23.097 --> 00:03:23.680
Anything else?

00:03:23.680 --> 00:03:23.980
Yes.

00:03:23.980 --> 00:03:24.976
- You're comfortable.

00:03:24.976 --> 00:03:26.970
You look comfortable in that.

00:03:26.970 --> 00:03:28.777
- Comfort is a
psychological state.

00:03:28.777 --> 00:03:30.360
If I were wearing
my corset, would you

00:03:30.360 --> 00:03:31.450
say I was comfortable?

00:03:31.450 --> 00:03:31.950
- No.

00:03:31.950 --> 00:03:33.870
- Probably you
wouldn't think so.

00:03:33.870 --> 00:03:34.860
One more thing.

00:03:34.860 --> 00:03:35.723
Anything else?

00:03:35.723 --> 00:03:36.490
- Pants.

00:03:36.490 --> 00:03:39.210
- Pants, that's right,
different than her.

00:03:39.210 --> 00:03:43.560
So that's one of the key gender
differentials for centuries

00:03:43.560 --> 00:03:45.360
in the West, that
women have been

00:03:45.360 --> 00:03:48.120
wearing some kind of
long skirt or dress,

00:03:48.120 --> 00:03:51.690
and men have been wearing
some bifurcated garment,

00:03:51.690 --> 00:03:54.780
in this case tights
rather than trousers.

00:03:54.780 --> 00:03:57.340
So let's see.

00:03:57.340 --> 00:03:58.750
We'll just move on a little bit.

00:03:58.750 --> 00:04:01.270
Another aspect of
fashion is, in addition

00:04:01.270 --> 00:04:05.920
to gender differentiation,
it has also frequently tended

00:04:05.920 --> 00:04:11.260
to highlight sexual or secondary
sexual characteristics.

00:04:11.260 --> 00:04:13.270
We usually think of
this in modern times

00:04:13.270 --> 00:04:16.269
as breasts and hips and bums.

00:04:16.269 --> 00:04:18.339
But, of course, in
the Renaissance,

00:04:18.339 --> 00:04:23.894
the codpiece highlighted
the male penis.

00:04:23.894 --> 00:04:29.340
If you go from
roughly 1860 to 1955,

00:04:29.340 --> 00:04:34.140
you find, also, this fairly
rigid sexual dimorphism

00:04:34.140 --> 00:04:35.220
in clothing.

00:04:35.220 --> 00:04:37.710
Now, if you looked
at other cultures,

00:04:37.710 --> 00:04:40.920
like Japan or
Indonesia, or if you

00:04:40.920 --> 00:04:42.900
looked at 18th-century
Europe, you

00:04:42.900 --> 00:04:44.910
might not be quite so stark.

00:04:44.910 --> 00:04:47.670
Because in 18th-century
Europe, upper-class couple

00:04:47.670 --> 00:04:50.400
might both be wearing a
pink, silk suit embroidered

00:04:50.400 --> 00:04:52.080
with flowers and lace.

00:04:52.080 --> 00:04:54.930
And in Indonesia, they'd
both be wearing sarongs.

00:04:54.930 --> 00:04:57.640
But it wouldn't be the same.

00:04:57.640 --> 00:05:00.120
I mean, I remember in
Indonesia, foreigners

00:05:00.120 --> 00:05:03.630
kept wrapping the sarongs the
wrong way for the other sex.

00:05:03.630 --> 00:05:06.935
And people would tell
them, you got it all wrong.

00:05:06.935 --> 00:05:07.810
You're crossdressing.

00:05:07.810 --> 00:05:10.080
And people were, eh, who cares?

00:05:10.080 --> 00:05:12.870
But it was very upsetting
to the Indonesians

00:05:12.870 --> 00:05:15.510
to see people doing that.

00:05:15.510 --> 00:05:19.860
And then this classic image
of mid-century Americana where

00:05:19.860 --> 00:05:22.950
the different clothes also have
very much to do with different

00:05:22.950 --> 00:05:23.790
roles--

00:05:23.790 --> 00:05:25.680
goes right back to
the chimpanzees.

00:05:25.680 --> 00:05:28.110
So you've got the
going out and fighting

00:05:28.110 --> 00:05:30.600
in the world versus staying
home with the kiddies.

00:05:30.600 --> 00:05:35.660
But notice, also, the very
dressed-up homemaker look.

00:05:35.660 --> 00:05:39.030
At that time, you have books
like Wife Dressing, which

00:05:39.030 --> 00:05:41.460
emphasized that you had
to dress in a feminine way

00:05:41.460 --> 00:05:43.980
so your children
would model correctly

00:05:43.980 --> 00:05:45.840
what women were
supposed to be like,

00:05:45.840 --> 00:05:47.850
and you should never
wear blue jeans at home.

00:05:47.850 --> 00:05:49.267
Even if you're
cleaning the floor,

00:05:49.267 --> 00:05:52.500
you should wear a girdle so you
looked appropriately feminine.

00:05:52.500 --> 00:05:54.750
So a lot of it had
to do with clothing

00:05:54.750 --> 00:05:58.290
being used to condition you
for appropriate roleplay.

00:05:58.290 --> 00:06:01.230
Obviously, there were
self-conscious attempts

00:06:01.230 --> 00:06:04.050
to change that with unisex.

00:06:04.050 --> 00:06:07.860
Rudi Gernreich developed this
unisex style for men and women,

00:06:07.860 --> 00:06:12.570
particularly caftans, although
most attempts at unisex

00:06:12.570 --> 00:06:16.080
have been drawing on
the male vocabulary.

00:06:16.080 --> 00:06:20.880
As one lesbian put it in the
1980s, when cock is king,

00:06:20.880 --> 00:06:22.470
go for the codpiece.

00:06:22.470 --> 00:06:26.010
There's no point in copying the
clothing of the weaker and more

00:06:26.010 --> 00:06:27.120
despised sex.

00:06:27.120 --> 00:06:29.910
You ought to copy the
clothing of the powerful sex.

00:06:29.910 --> 00:06:33.810
And in fact, it's fairly rare
that men have copied things

00:06:33.810 --> 00:06:35.770
from the female wardrobe.

00:06:35.770 --> 00:06:38.640
It was really
extraordinarily rare as late

00:06:38.640 --> 00:06:42.090
as the 1970s for men to
wear earrings, for example.

00:06:42.090 --> 00:06:46.800
And only gradually, particularly
with sports figures doing it,

00:06:46.800 --> 00:06:50.400
did regular men get in touch
with their inner pirate

00:06:50.400 --> 00:06:53.010
and take back earrings
from the female wardrobe

00:06:53.010 --> 00:06:55.320
and say, no, we can
wear earrings, too.

00:06:55.320 --> 00:06:57.780
In general, the idea is
to dress like someone

00:06:57.780 --> 00:07:00.450
who has more power.

00:07:00.450 --> 00:07:03.300
You see it with uniforms, too.

00:07:03.300 --> 00:07:05.730
Police women in
the United States

00:07:05.730 --> 00:07:08.430
used to have to
wear a skirted suit.

00:07:08.430 --> 00:07:12.360
In many states, they also
had a smaller gun, which

00:07:12.360 --> 00:07:15.660
they had to carry in a purse.

00:07:15.660 --> 00:07:19.830
They also had to wear shoes
with heels and sometimes

00:07:19.830 --> 00:07:21.450
a stupid little hat.

00:07:21.450 --> 00:07:24.930
As one woman who later became
a police captain in Virginia

00:07:24.930 --> 00:07:27.420
put it, you can imagine
it was hard to chase

00:07:27.420 --> 00:07:30.290
the perpetrator when you
were dressed like that.

00:07:30.290 --> 00:07:32.040
But the point is, you
weren't supposed to.

00:07:32.040 --> 00:07:33.540
You were supposed
to be doing things

00:07:33.540 --> 00:07:36.210
like helping lost children.

00:07:36.210 --> 00:07:39.180
Later on, when the
federal legislation

00:07:39.180 --> 00:07:42.360
was passed mandating
equal opportunities,

00:07:42.360 --> 00:07:47.090
including equal kinds of
uniforms for police officers.

00:07:47.090 --> 00:07:49.870
Now, I'm going to talk
about several aspects

00:07:49.870 --> 00:07:51.940
of my own research
over the years, which

00:07:51.940 --> 00:07:55.560
have tended to focus on sex
and gender issues in fashion.

00:07:55.560 --> 00:07:57.390
And people seem to
write the same--

00:07:57.390 --> 00:08:00.500
my friends said we all write the
same book over and over again,

00:08:00.500 --> 00:08:03.880
intended to be this way for me.

00:08:03.880 --> 00:08:08.380
Corsets were the way I got into
fashion in the first place.

00:08:08.380 --> 00:08:09.820
I had a very checkered history.

00:08:09.820 --> 00:08:11.530
I dropped out of high
school, ran away,

00:08:11.530 --> 00:08:13.720
lived in a
lesbian-feminist commune,

00:08:13.720 --> 00:08:16.120
never finished high school,
couldn't get into Harvard,

00:08:16.120 --> 00:08:16.840
was rejected.

00:08:16.840 --> 00:08:19.960
They said, you're
not Harvard material.

00:08:19.960 --> 00:08:22.860
But I ended up later on going
to graduate school at Yale.

00:08:22.860 --> 00:08:26.710
And my first term at Yale--

00:08:26.710 --> 00:08:29.260
I was there studying modern
European cultural history.

00:08:29.260 --> 00:08:33.130
We had to give a report
on two scholarly articles.

00:08:33.130 --> 00:08:34.960
I don't remember what I read.

00:08:34.960 --> 00:08:37.210
I assume it was something
about the French Revolution.

00:08:37.210 --> 00:08:40.870
But my classmate, Judy Coffin,
reported on two articles

00:08:40.870 --> 00:08:44.500
from the feminist journal
Signs arguing about the meaning

00:08:44.500 --> 00:08:46.150
of the Victorian corset.

00:08:46.150 --> 00:08:49.580
Was it oppressive to women,
or was it sexually liberating?

00:08:49.580 --> 00:08:51.550
And it was just like
a light bulb went on,

00:08:51.550 --> 00:08:54.280
and I realized fashion's
part of culture.

00:08:54.280 --> 00:08:56.030
I can do fashion history.

00:08:56.030 --> 00:08:58.780
So I did, thereby
destroying any opportunity

00:08:58.780 --> 00:09:03.710
of having a career in academia.

00:09:03.710 --> 00:09:07.570
But this is the image that
people have of corsetry.

00:09:07.570 --> 00:09:09.760
This is an 18th-century
caricature,

00:09:09.760 --> 00:09:11.230
but people always think of--

00:09:11.230 --> 00:09:13.090
I wish I had a
dollar for every time

00:09:13.090 --> 00:09:15.670
I've heard someone in
a corset exhibition

00:09:15.670 --> 00:09:20.120
saying, remember Scarlett
O'Hara and the 16-inch waist?

00:09:20.120 --> 00:09:23.810
This is really hardwired
into everyone's memory.

00:09:23.810 --> 00:09:26.410
In fact, men sometimes
wore corsets, too.

00:09:26.410 --> 00:09:31.240
And you have exactly the same
type of caricature for dandies.

00:09:31.240 --> 00:09:34.990
But tight lacing was
really a very small part

00:09:34.990 --> 00:09:41.200
of what corsetry meant in
the more than 300, 400 years

00:09:41.200 --> 00:09:48.260
that it lasted, from about
1500 into the mid-20th century.

00:09:48.260 --> 00:09:50.770
So if you look at something
like Manet's Nana.

00:09:50.770 --> 00:09:54.190
You see that part of what's
going on with the corset

00:09:54.190 --> 00:09:57.880
is it's not just a waist
cincher, which would emphasize

00:09:57.880 --> 00:10:02.812
what anthropologists call
the waist-hip differential,

00:10:02.812 --> 00:10:06.260
much bigger in a
woman than a man.

00:10:06.260 --> 00:10:08.890
For a young woman,
it might be 0.7.

00:10:08.890 --> 00:10:10.660
For a man, it would be 0.9.

00:10:10.660 --> 00:10:13.420
In other words, the waist
is 9/10 of the size.

00:10:13.420 --> 00:10:15.670
But also, it's like a brassiere.

00:10:15.670 --> 00:10:18.640
It's pushing your bust
up and supporting it.

00:10:18.640 --> 00:10:21.450
And it's also an element
of underwear, in this case

00:10:21.450 --> 00:10:24.460
luxurious, blue,
satin underwear.

00:10:24.460 --> 00:10:26.830
At this time, people
thought of that kind

00:10:26.830 --> 00:10:29.290
of luxurious underwear
as associated

00:10:29.290 --> 00:10:31.570
with the aristocracy of vice.

00:10:31.570 --> 00:10:34.210
Only courtesans and
actresses wore that.

00:10:34.210 --> 00:10:39.730
But very soon afterwards, any
fashionable women did, too.

00:10:39.730 --> 00:10:42.085
These are from the
mostly men's magazine

00:10:42.085 --> 00:10:46.750
La Vie Parisienne centerfolds
before and after the corset.

00:10:46.750 --> 00:10:49.490
Improved-- for example,
if you were too skinny,

00:10:49.490 --> 00:10:52.150
you were padded out,
which is very common.

00:10:52.150 --> 00:10:54.130
We think of corsets just
squeezing people in,

00:10:54.130 --> 00:10:57.360
but padded corsets
are extremely common.

00:10:57.360 --> 00:10:59.860
Corsets, which, in the middle,
the woman's figure's supposed

00:10:59.860 --> 00:11:02.320
to be great, but her
breasts are starting to sag,

00:11:02.320 --> 00:11:04.660
so you lift them up, et cetera.

00:11:04.660 --> 00:11:08.410
As one doctor put it
in a book in the middle

00:11:08.410 --> 00:11:12.460
of the 19th century,
a corset is a lie,

00:11:12.460 --> 00:11:15.670
but we prefer the
lie to the truth.

00:11:15.670 --> 00:11:17.770
So the idea was it was
going to improve all

00:11:17.770 --> 00:11:21.700
of these flawed female bodies.

00:11:21.700 --> 00:11:24.310
And then you have
another centerfold

00:11:24.310 --> 00:11:27.460
looking at different
kinds of corsets, anything

00:11:27.460 --> 00:11:31.300
from the young girl's
very simple bust bodice

00:11:31.300 --> 00:11:37.150
to the one with the black
corset and the blue stockings,

00:11:37.150 --> 00:11:38.920
the laundress who's
thinking of going

00:11:38.920 --> 00:11:44.320
bad, to this elaborate colorful
satin and vulgarly trimmed

00:11:44.320 --> 00:11:46.720
corsets that
cocottes would wear,

00:11:46.720 --> 00:11:49.210
corsets that were
scented so they'd

00:11:49.210 --> 00:11:52.960
smell more as they got hotter.

00:11:52.960 --> 00:11:55.990
But the woman in the
center has no corset.

00:11:55.990 --> 00:11:58.270
She's just wearing
a silk undershirt.

00:11:58.270 --> 00:12:00.640
And they say that,
actually, that

00:12:00.640 --> 00:12:02.830
would be best, is
what they say, if you

00:12:02.830 --> 00:12:04.090
didn't have to wear a corset.

00:12:04.090 --> 00:12:07.570
Unfortunately, they say, there's
usually more need for one

00:12:07.570 --> 00:12:10.810
rather than less.

00:12:10.810 --> 00:12:16.720
But what's interesting is
already by about the 1890s,

00:12:16.720 --> 00:12:20.080
and certainly by
1900, 1902, you see

00:12:20.080 --> 00:12:22.960
more and more
photographs of women,

00:12:22.960 --> 00:12:25.570
actresses, et cetera,
wearing corsets

00:12:25.570 --> 00:12:28.090
and then they're fit
in their fashions.

00:12:28.090 --> 00:12:30.580
And they interview these
ladies and they say,

00:12:30.580 --> 00:12:32.380
who's your favorite couturier?

00:12:32.380 --> 00:12:34.060
Who's your favorite jeweler?

00:12:34.060 --> 00:12:35.890
Who's your favorite corsetiere?

00:12:35.890 --> 00:12:38.530
And very often the
women will say,

00:12:38.530 --> 00:12:40.510
I don't need to wear a corset.

00:12:40.510 --> 00:12:42.510
And you look at the
photograph and you go, babe,

00:12:42.510 --> 00:12:44.050
you are so wearing a corset.

00:12:44.050 --> 00:12:45.070
[LAUGHTER]

00:12:45.070 --> 00:12:48.400
But it's already started to
seem that it will be better

00:12:48.400 --> 00:12:49.810
if you didn't need to wear one.

