00:26:06.760 --> 00:26:09.610
And so this idea of
his look at first

00:26:09.610 --> 00:26:14.920
was something which mixed male
and female signifiers as well

00:26:14.920 --> 00:26:17.350
as historicizing and
aristocratic things

00:26:17.350 --> 00:26:19.960
like showing off the
legs in knee breeches

00:26:19.960 --> 00:26:21.790
and wearing velvet,
which was associated

00:26:21.790 --> 00:26:24.340
as a woman's material.

00:26:24.340 --> 00:26:27.820
This came from a book, George
Chauncey's Gay New York,

00:26:27.820 --> 00:26:29.805
from a 19th-century
guide of types

00:26:29.805 --> 00:26:33.460
you might see in New York,
including, on the Upper Side,

00:26:33.460 --> 00:26:36.730
a man who'd be wearing a
short jacket and tight pants

00:26:36.730 --> 00:26:40.518
and might have
curly, longer hair.

00:26:40.518 --> 00:26:43.830
And then the whole idea
of the dandy, which became

00:26:43.830 --> 00:26:46.170
a really important gay icon--

00:26:46.170 --> 00:26:48.060
here in a kind of
almost butterfly

00:26:48.060 --> 00:26:53.380
dandy style with Count
Robert de Montesquiou.

00:26:53.380 --> 00:26:56.830
And then here in the kind of
female dandy-- the very, very

00:26:56.830 --> 00:26:59.860
important
early-20th-century lesbian

00:26:59.860 --> 00:27:03.220
look, which, again, is borrowing
from the male upper-class

00:27:03.220 --> 00:27:04.270
wardrobe.

00:27:04.270 --> 00:27:06.850
Extremely important,
pivotal look

00:27:06.850 --> 00:27:09.940
in the history of
lesbian fashion

00:27:09.940 --> 00:27:12.460
and also of women's
fashion in general.

00:27:12.460 --> 00:27:16.630
So you saw it ubiquitously
in, say, Brassai's photographs

00:27:16.630 --> 00:27:19.210
of lesbian bars in Paris.

00:27:19.210 --> 00:27:22.810
And you also saw it in
images of fashionable women

00:27:22.810 --> 00:27:24.730
as that whole kind
of garcon look

00:27:24.730 --> 00:27:29.170
took over as being
the fashionable style.

00:27:29.170 --> 00:27:31.930
Marlene Dietrich, of
course, who really

00:27:31.930 --> 00:27:34.450
was an important figure
in terms not only

00:27:34.450 --> 00:27:37.780
of wearing full-scale men's
dress off-screen as well

00:27:37.780 --> 00:27:41.470
as on-screen, but also
pioneering wearing trousers

00:27:41.470 --> 00:27:43.870
and being a sort
of bisexual icon

00:27:43.870 --> 00:27:47.340
for fashion people
for generations.

00:27:47.340 --> 00:27:49.050
We got some of
her clothes, which

00:27:49.050 --> 00:27:55.420
we posed next to the Saint
Laurent in Queer History.

00:27:55.420 --> 00:27:57.670
And then, of course,
one of the key reasons

00:27:57.670 --> 00:28:01.210
why you have LGBTQ
styles has been a way

00:28:01.210 --> 00:28:04.570
to signal in a hostile
society so that you could meet

00:28:04.570 --> 00:28:08.740
other people who would also be
queer and without cluing out

00:28:08.740 --> 00:28:11.350
people who might be
straight and hostile.

00:28:11.350 --> 00:28:15.040
So those varied, but they
included things like dyed hair,

00:28:15.040 --> 00:28:19.230
red tie, suede shoes, et cetera.

00:28:19.230 --> 00:28:23.010
Yves Saint Laurent posed
here on leather cushions

00:28:23.010 --> 00:28:26.680
for his early perfume ad--

00:28:26.680 --> 00:28:31.240
and then the very much
politicized gay styles

00:28:31.240 --> 00:28:35.210
of the AIDS era and beyond.

00:28:35.210 --> 00:28:38.120
And then we haven't even
talked about the erotic appeal

00:28:38.120 --> 00:28:39.290
of the uniform--

00:28:39.290 --> 00:28:42.290
but is one which goes
right back in history so

00:28:42.290 --> 00:28:46.070
that both male and female
brothels in 19th-century Paris

00:28:46.070 --> 00:28:48.350
had a range of uniforms.

00:28:48.350 --> 00:28:52.790
So people who had a fetish for
nuns or a fetish for soldiers

00:28:52.790 --> 00:28:56.180
from a particular regiment
or sailors or brides

00:28:56.180 --> 00:28:59.746
could find all those
costumes at the brothel.

00:28:59.746 --> 00:29:01.620
And then I'll just
show you, so you

00:29:01.620 --> 00:29:05.130
can see how
advertising for fashion

00:29:05.130 --> 00:29:07.650
picks up on not just
gender stereotypes,

00:29:07.650 --> 00:29:10.770
but also a lot of
sexual stereotypes.

00:29:10.770 --> 00:29:14.820
These are a few years old,
so this is no longer--

00:29:14.820 --> 00:29:19.090
obviously, no longer current
Balenciaga, nor current Gucci.

00:29:19.090 --> 00:29:20.790
The current Gucci
ads couldn't possibly

00:29:20.790 --> 00:29:23.730
be any more different than this.

00:29:23.730 --> 00:29:25.590
Hugo Boss is like--

00:29:25.590 --> 00:29:26.770
same with the Hermes--

00:29:26.770 --> 00:29:28.830
that's like rich
people's white clothes.

00:29:28.830 --> 00:29:30.660
[LAUGHTER]

00:29:30.660 --> 00:29:33.240
And then this is
probably Saint Laurent.

00:29:33.240 --> 00:29:35.250
But, again, it's that sort of--

00:29:35.250 --> 00:29:37.260
it's the hipster,
cool, rock chick

00:29:37.260 --> 00:29:41.010
look, which is ubiquitous
in fashion advertising.

00:29:41.010 --> 00:29:43.800
Céline, which was, for a
while, the sort of smart

00:29:43.800 --> 00:29:46.950
women's fashion that was not
going to be all these sexual

00:29:46.950 --> 00:29:50.420
stereotypes-- kind of
quirky women's style.

00:29:50.420 --> 00:29:56.120
And then, although women may
not be as often sexual fetishes

00:29:56.120 --> 00:29:59.660
like men, certainly,
commodity fetishism

00:29:59.660 --> 00:30:02.480
is running rampant
throughout society.

00:30:02.480 --> 00:30:05.210
And that, as they
say, is another story.

00:30:05.210 --> 00:30:09.230
But it's an incredibly important
part of the fashion story

00:30:09.230 --> 00:30:10.410
as well.

00:30:10.410 --> 00:30:12.428
So thank you very much.

00:30:12.428 --> 00:30:14.300
[APPLAUSE]

00:30:18.044 --> 00:30:21.610
- So thank you, Valerie,
for a wonderful talk.

00:30:21.610 --> 00:30:24.190
We have time for questions.

00:30:24.190 --> 00:30:27.540
Again, please come
to the center.

00:30:27.540 --> 00:30:29.400
And I know there'll
be a lot of people

00:30:29.400 --> 00:30:34.210
who want to ask questions,
so please ask questions.

00:30:34.210 --> 00:30:37.285
Keep the questions short
so that we can accommodate

00:30:37.285 --> 00:30:38.410
as many people as possible.

00:30:38.410 --> 00:30:40.090
- Thank you so much, Dr. Steele.

00:30:40.090 --> 00:30:44.350
I was intrigued and troubled
by Professor Peters' comment

00:30:44.350 --> 00:30:47.260
earlier today that
sex is the naked body,

00:30:47.260 --> 00:30:49.570
and gender is the clothed body.

00:30:49.570 --> 00:30:52.180
I was wondering if you
wanted to either trouble

00:30:52.180 --> 00:30:56.890
or expand on that idea, in
particular around the idea

00:30:56.890 --> 00:31:00.220
of gender-nonconforming
fashion and the way

00:31:00.220 --> 00:31:04.630
that sexuality and fetishism
has been de-emphasized

00:31:04.630 --> 00:31:08.740
in new designers looking to
promote a nonbinary idea.

00:31:08.740 --> 00:31:09.520
- Right.

00:31:09.520 --> 00:31:14.110
Well, people always-- a
lot of people hate fashion.

00:31:14.110 --> 00:31:16.960
And one of the main
crimes of fashion

00:31:16.960 --> 00:31:20.140
is it's seen as being
artificial, not natural.

00:31:20.140 --> 00:31:23.440
But the idea that the
body itself is natural

00:31:23.440 --> 00:31:26.380
is, of course, a
complete fantasy

00:31:26.380 --> 00:31:31.540
because we structure our
bodies in innumerable ways--

00:31:31.540 --> 00:31:33.940
that we're taught
to stand and walk.

00:31:33.940 --> 00:31:35.020
We cut our hair.

00:31:35.020 --> 00:31:35.830
We shave.

00:31:35.830 --> 00:31:38.890
We do all kinds of
things to our bodies.

00:31:38.890 --> 00:31:43.420
And, really, I think rather than
pitting body versus clothing,

00:31:43.420 --> 00:31:46.840
it's more useful when you're
thinking of the relationship

00:31:46.840 --> 00:31:49.270
to think of the
body-clothes unit

00:31:49.270 --> 00:31:54.520
as being what you're using to
convey aspects of identity.

00:31:54.520 --> 00:31:56.920
So the very same garment--

00:31:56.920 --> 00:31:59.830
say, a corset-- is going
to convey different things

00:31:59.830 --> 00:32:03.400
on a male or a female body, and
depending on what kind of body

00:32:03.400 --> 00:32:04.110
it is.

00:32:04.110 --> 00:32:06.370
Blue jeans
historically were seen

00:32:06.370 --> 00:32:09.550
as being something that
molded to a variety

00:32:09.550 --> 00:32:12.310
of different bodies and told
sort of different stories

00:32:12.310 --> 00:32:17.935
about who you were
because the garment was

00:32:17.935 --> 00:32:20.760
in close connection
with the body.

00:32:20.760 --> 00:32:22.660
Now give me the second
half of the question

00:32:22.660 --> 00:32:25.615
again about how
fashion has been--

00:32:25.615 --> 00:32:30.580
- --sort of desexualized from
designers that are promoting

00:32:30.580 --> 00:32:34.390
gender-nonconforming aesthetic
and how does that filter

00:32:34.390 --> 00:32:39.050
in with the kind of sexiness of
the fetish [INAUDIBLE] world.

00:32:39.050 --> 00:32:46.540
- I think that some designers
have tried to de-emphasize

00:32:46.540 --> 00:32:51.010
overt sexual
characteristics in clothing.

00:32:51.010 --> 00:32:55.480
But others have,
in fact, stretched

00:32:55.480 --> 00:32:59.620
the idea of taking something
which might be stereotypically

00:32:59.620 --> 00:33:03.100
sexy in one area and
seeing what happens if you

00:33:03.100 --> 00:33:04.660
have other people wear it.

00:33:04.660 --> 00:33:07.810
So, for example, pink
has, in the West,

00:33:07.810 --> 00:33:12.070
been seen as a feminine
color for quite some time.

00:33:12.070 --> 00:33:15.160
And yet over the
last 10 or 15 years,

00:33:15.160 --> 00:33:17.890
it's been more and more
appropriated by men,

00:33:17.890 --> 00:33:21.560
and it's acquired a
range of other meanings.

00:33:21.560 --> 00:33:24.220
It's been associated
with the LGBTQ community

00:33:24.220 --> 00:33:26.920
and, particularly, with
sort of queer radicals

00:33:26.920 --> 00:33:28.930
within it who see
the rainbow as being

00:33:28.930 --> 00:33:34.370
more bourgeois and pink as being
a more radical queer color.

00:33:34.370 --> 00:33:37.750
It also was picked
up in a very big way

00:33:37.750 --> 00:33:42.130
by African-American men,
particularly coming out

00:33:42.130 --> 00:33:44.150
of the whole hip-hop experience.

00:33:44.150 --> 00:33:47.590
And it took about 10
years for Caucasian men

00:33:47.590 --> 00:33:50.980
to start tiptoeing
towards the kind of pink

00:33:50.980 --> 00:33:53.500
is this sort of
masculine or, at least,

00:33:53.500 --> 00:33:57.580
androgynous color, although you
had a long history within rock

00:33:57.580 --> 00:34:01.510
and roll and earlier
musical forms of pink

00:34:01.510 --> 00:34:04.390
as being a rebellious color.

00:34:04.390 --> 00:34:07.090
Now, Elvis wore pink, of
course, and had a pink Cadillac.

00:34:07.090 --> 00:34:09.909
But in that way, he was
actually copying, probably,

00:34:09.909 --> 00:34:14.199
Sugar Ray Robinson, the
African-American boxer.

00:34:14.199 --> 00:34:17.739
And then later on, the bass
guitarist for The Clash

00:34:17.739 --> 00:34:21.100
said how pink was the only
real rock and roll color.

00:34:21.100 --> 00:34:26.590
So you can destabilize
the sort of sexualization

00:34:26.590 --> 00:34:30.310
either by trying to do something
which is gender neutral,

00:34:30.310 --> 00:34:33.070
which is really kind of
hard to do because it's

00:34:33.070 --> 00:34:35.620
almost always going to
tilt towards, I think,

00:34:35.620 --> 00:34:39.070
the male clothing vocabulary.

00:34:39.070 --> 00:34:42.670
You can get men in
skirts or caftans,

00:34:42.670 --> 00:34:44.275
but it's a harder sell.

00:34:44.275 --> 00:34:46.750
You got them in earrings, so
you can get them in anything.

00:34:46.750 --> 00:34:48.450
But it's a harder sell.

00:34:48.450 --> 00:34:52.030
But, also, you can destabilize
the symbolism of something

00:34:52.030 --> 00:34:55.480
which has been seen as feminine
and sort of rebrand it.

00:34:55.480 --> 00:34:57.760
But I think, very often,
to make it popular,

00:34:57.760 --> 00:35:00.730
you don't rebrand it as asexual.

00:35:00.730 --> 00:35:04.180
You brand it as being
kind of both sexual

00:35:04.180 --> 00:35:06.490
or a range of sexual
because, really,

00:35:06.490 --> 00:35:08.740
how many people want
to be sexually neutral.

00:35:08.740 --> 00:35:10.930
They want to have
their own expression

00:35:10.930 --> 00:35:13.810
of their own sexuality,
whatever that is.

00:35:13.810 --> 00:35:16.300
But, usually, except
for people who

00:35:16.300 --> 00:35:18.130
really identify as asexual--

00:35:18.130 --> 00:35:22.870
usually, they do want to have
some kind of a sexual appeal

00:35:22.870 --> 00:35:26.060
to other people or
to some other people.

00:35:26.060 --> 00:35:26.560
Yeah?

00:35:26.560 --> 00:35:27.510
- Hi.

00:35:27.510 --> 00:35:29.190
I have a question
that I hope may

00:35:29.190 --> 00:35:31.570
resonate with some
other folks in the room.

00:35:31.570 --> 00:35:33.720
So my identity for as
long as I can remember

00:35:33.720 --> 00:35:36.210
has been around being
an intellectual being,

00:35:36.210 --> 00:35:39.630
and so this idea
that I give time

00:35:39.630 --> 00:35:43.590
to think about how I present
myself was antithetical.

00:35:43.590 --> 00:35:47.190
And so it's only very
recently that I got a real job

00:35:47.190 --> 00:35:49.620
and had money to spend on
fashion that I've started

00:35:49.620 --> 00:35:52.230
to think maybe this is
a variable in my life

00:35:52.230 --> 00:35:53.820
that I can play with.

00:35:53.820 --> 00:35:55.740
Do you have any advice?

00:35:55.740 --> 00:35:56.980
[LAUGHTER]

00:35:57.480 --> 00:35:58.290
Well, no.

00:35:58.290 --> 00:36:00.230
Well, OK.

00:36:00.230 --> 00:36:02.730
Again, other people in this
room are also at Harvard, right?

00:36:02.730 --> 00:36:04.930
Harvard has a very
particular style.

00:36:04.930 --> 00:36:06.510
I was educated at MIT--

00:36:06.510 --> 00:36:09.210
very different style there.

00:36:09.210 --> 00:36:11.500
So we're professional folks.

00:36:11.500 --> 00:36:13.123
We also have private lives.

00:36:13.123 --> 00:36:14.790
And I'm just curious
about your thoughts

00:36:14.790 --> 00:36:18.210
about being intellectuals who
also care about how we dress.

00:36:18.210 --> 00:36:19.300
- Yeah.

00:36:19.300 --> 00:36:22.440
This is something that
I have experienced

00:36:22.440 --> 00:36:24.645
from the very
beginning of my career.

00:36:27.320 --> 00:36:31.010
Fashion is despised widely
in American society.

00:36:31.010 --> 00:36:35.960
But it is especially despised
within American academia.

00:36:35.960 --> 00:36:37.790
I wrote an article
once called "The F

00:36:37.790 --> 00:36:41.150
Word," which was in Lingua
Franca, the academic journal.

00:36:41.150 --> 00:36:45.020
And I literally could not
get any academic colleagues

00:36:45.020 --> 00:36:48.770
to go on record with
their name to say anything

00:36:48.770 --> 00:36:52.490
about fashion because they
didn't want to be associated

00:36:52.490 --> 00:36:54.980
with it at all, even
people who I knew

00:36:54.980 --> 00:36:58.610
were quite interested in
fashion, because the idea is

00:36:58.610 --> 00:37:01.760
that the life of the mind
means that the life of the body

00:37:01.760 --> 00:37:05.750
is immaterial, especially
when it's not even the body,

00:37:05.750 --> 00:37:09.140
but it's like this
flayed extra skin,

00:37:09.140 --> 00:37:13.520
this low, bourgeois,
anti-feminist, consumerist,

00:37:13.520 --> 00:37:17.720
conformist thing that somehow
you have to put on your body.

00:37:17.720 --> 00:37:22.940
But we intellectuals really
don't follow any style.

00:37:22.940 --> 00:37:24.680
And, to some
extent, that's true.

00:37:24.680 --> 00:37:26.870
I mean, I would say
academics are probably

00:37:26.870 --> 00:37:30.680
the worst-dressed middle-class
occupational group in America.

00:37:30.680 --> 00:37:34.940
But, nevertheless, they are
buying their own clothes.

00:37:34.940 --> 00:37:38.060
In only a handful of instances
are their mothers still buying

00:37:38.060 --> 00:37:39.230
their clothes.

00:37:39.230 --> 00:37:42.860
And, therefore, it behooves
them to take some responsibility

00:37:42.860 --> 00:37:47.060
for their clothes and decide
what makes them happy to wear.

00:37:47.060 --> 00:37:48.645
And I think that's
really the answer.

00:37:48.645 --> 00:37:51.020
Of course, we said you look
comfortable in what you wear.

00:37:51.020 --> 00:37:55.070
Basically, especially now,
there are very few social rules,

00:37:55.070 --> 00:37:58.400
even in the job situation,
about what you have to wear.

00:37:58.400 --> 00:38:00.380
So you might as well
try and figure out

00:38:00.380 --> 00:38:05.240
what makes you happy to
wear because, otherwise, you

00:38:05.240 --> 00:38:07.430
can just outsource it to mom.

00:38:07.430 --> 00:38:08.180
She'll pay for it.

00:38:08.180 --> 00:38:11.120
But apart from that, there's
probably a downside to that

00:38:11.120 --> 00:38:13.940
as well because it does
sort of convey something

00:38:13.940 --> 00:38:17.500
about who you are and
what you think you are

00:38:17.500 --> 00:38:20.490
and that you do, in fact,
think about who you are,

00:38:20.490 --> 00:38:23.185
which is not a bad thing
to do even for a brainiac.

00:38:25.830 --> 00:38:27.150
- Hi.

00:38:27.150 --> 00:38:30.090
So you mentioned when you
were talking about the corset

00:38:30.090 --> 00:38:33.180
that there is a lot of
interactions between women

00:38:33.180 --> 00:38:37.040
wanting to borrow from a
masculine style that is either

00:38:37.040 --> 00:38:39.930
of a higher class or of
a gender association that

00:38:39.930 --> 00:38:41.110
has more power.

00:38:41.110 --> 00:38:44.520
I actually took a really
brilliant class at school

00:38:44.520 --> 00:38:47.100
at Harvard taught by
Professor Jonathan

00:38:47.100 --> 00:38:49.163
Square on fashion and slavery.

00:38:49.163 --> 00:38:51.330
And I was wondering if you
could talk more about how

00:38:51.330 --> 00:38:53.288
you see the sort of
interaction-- you mentioned

00:38:53.288 --> 00:38:55.677
Gucci is really changing the
way that it presents itself,

00:38:55.677 --> 00:38:57.510
and a lot of that has
to do with streetwear.

00:38:57.510 --> 00:39:00.590
And I was wondering if you had
any thoughts on how streetwear

00:39:00.590 --> 00:39:03.930
is becoming to be so
powerful in fashion

00:39:03.930 --> 00:39:06.360
and how design houses
have historically

00:39:06.360 --> 00:39:08.890
borrowed from marginalized
populations as well.

00:39:08.890 --> 00:39:11.850
- Yeah, absolutely.

00:39:11.850 --> 00:39:14.940
The standard old sort of
19th-century Veblenesque thing

00:39:14.940 --> 00:39:18.060
is that the fashions are set
up high, and they trickle down,

00:39:18.060 --> 00:39:21.420
and that middle-class people
imitate upper-class people.

00:39:21.420 --> 00:39:26.160
However, very often-- and even
at least as early as the 18th

00:39:26.160 --> 00:39:29.520
century and probably earlier,
although my own studies

00:39:29.520 --> 00:39:31.830
don't go really before
the 18th century--

00:39:31.830 --> 00:39:35.820
you found elite people borrowing
from working-class dress

00:39:35.820 --> 00:39:39.190
and sometimes even
borrowing cross-culturally

00:39:39.190 --> 00:39:41.490
so that in 18th-century
London, there

00:39:41.490 --> 00:39:45.090
were upper-class men who were
wearing styles of coats which

00:39:45.090 --> 00:39:47.460
were like the kind of
thing that coachman wore

00:39:47.460 --> 00:39:51.270
and definitely affecting a
kind of rough working-class

00:39:51.270 --> 00:39:52.680
demeanor.

00:39:52.680 --> 00:39:56.580
And then you also had some
who were cutting their hair

00:39:56.580 --> 00:39:58.000
like mohawk haircuts--

00:39:58.000 --> 00:40:00.450
I mean, sort of centuries
before the punks.

00:40:00.450 --> 00:40:04.680
So you had this kind of
appropriation frequently.

00:40:04.680 --> 00:40:09.720
I think it has to do with
a very widespread fantasy

00:40:09.720 --> 00:40:12.750
that working-class men or
men of other ethnicities

00:40:12.750 --> 00:40:15.090
are more masculine
and more virile

00:40:15.090 --> 00:40:19.410
and that you can get that
if you can assimilate

00:40:19.410 --> 00:40:21.870
some aspect of their appearance.

00:40:21.870 --> 00:40:26.340
And then there's also all
kinds of middle-class leftists

00:40:26.340 --> 00:40:30.060
who, again, saw working-class
men as being not only probably

00:40:30.060 --> 00:40:33.690
more virile, but also more
sort of authentic and real.

00:40:33.690 --> 00:40:37.920
So you get that whole kind of
fantasy of-- it's this really

00:40:37.920 --> 00:40:41.010
kind of a variant of the fantasy
of a natural man or even sort

00:40:41.010 --> 00:40:42.210
of the natural savage--

00:40:42.210 --> 00:40:44.640
that you're going down
there, and you're finding

00:40:44.640 --> 00:40:46.050
somebody who's authentic.

00:40:46.050 --> 00:40:48.660
And you're trying to
get that authenticity.

00:40:48.660 --> 00:40:50.940
So you often will find--
you found that in the '60s

00:40:50.940 --> 00:40:54.810
all the time with the idea that
blue jeans or certain kinds

00:40:54.810 --> 00:40:57.150
of ethnic clothing
were more authentic

00:40:57.150 --> 00:40:59.580
than bourgeois fashion.

00:40:59.580 --> 00:41:02.160
So there are many,
many occasions

00:41:02.160 --> 00:41:07.600
when people have
appropriated styles of dress,

00:41:07.600 --> 00:41:08.820
hairstyle, tattooing.

00:41:08.820 --> 00:41:11.160
I mean, think of all
the endless styles--

00:41:11.160 --> 00:41:16.290
everything from Japanese to
Maori tattoos to Dayak tattoos

00:41:16.290 --> 00:41:18.085
that people have appropriated--

00:41:18.085 --> 00:41:19.710
although nobody
actually yet is talking

00:41:19.710 --> 00:41:22.080
about tattoo cultural
appropriation.

00:41:22.080 --> 00:41:25.080
But as with fashion,
it's there too.

00:41:25.080 --> 00:41:27.060
And there's usually
a sense that there's

00:41:27.060 --> 00:41:32.310
something more desirable,
more authentic in that culture

00:41:32.310 --> 00:41:35.750
than in your own culture.

00:41:35.750 --> 00:41:37.250
And, of course, the
fashion industry

00:41:37.250 --> 00:41:40.460
has been doing this
for a very long time.

00:41:40.460 --> 00:41:42.740
But, especially
since the 1960s--

00:41:42.740 --> 00:41:46.250
the idea that you're
copying streetwear.

00:41:46.250 --> 00:41:48.590
Also, you're copying
active sportswear.

00:41:48.590 --> 00:41:52.760
So there are huge numbers
of young people today

00:41:52.760 --> 00:41:55.100
who I think have never worn
a pair of leather shoes

00:41:55.100 --> 00:41:57.680
because they've
only worn sneakers.

00:41:57.680 --> 00:42:00.380
So that kind of thing becomes--

00:42:00.380 --> 00:42:03.620
it's, again, an association
with a cool factor.

00:42:03.620 --> 00:42:05.120
Who's wearing it?

00:42:05.120 --> 00:42:06.290
They're younger.

00:42:06.290 --> 00:42:07.620
Maybe they're hipper.

00:42:07.620 --> 00:42:10.130
They seem more
knowledgeable; more

00:42:10.130 --> 00:42:13.110
cool than just sort of
sheltered, middle-class kids.

00:42:13.110 --> 00:42:16.040
And so you want
to look like that.

00:42:16.040 --> 00:42:18.140
Never underestimate
the desire to look

00:42:18.140 --> 00:42:21.497
like somebody that's cooler than
you-- however that's defined.

00:42:21.497 --> 00:42:22.840
- OK.

00:42:22.840 --> 00:42:24.316
Final question.

00:42:24.316 --> 00:42:26.200
- So this kind of
follows on from that.

00:42:26.200 --> 00:42:29.050
One thing that struck me about
the two caricatures that you

00:42:29.050 --> 00:42:33.640
showed us of the corset--
like the tight lacing--

00:42:33.640 --> 00:42:36.880
was that in both of those
caricatures, we had--

00:42:36.880 --> 00:42:38.710
one of the people
doing the lace thing

00:42:38.710 --> 00:42:42.472
was a black man or a black boy.

00:42:42.472 --> 00:42:44.680
And so I was wondering
whether that was a coincidence

00:42:44.680 --> 00:42:46.097
or whether there's
something going

00:42:46.097 --> 00:42:49.640
on there about either class--

00:42:49.640 --> 00:42:50.940
the first one there is.

00:42:50.940 --> 00:42:51.940
Yeah, right at the back.

00:42:51.940 --> 00:42:52.580
And I thought--

00:42:52.580 --> 00:42:53.260
- --yeah.

00:42:53.260 --> 00:42:54.956
Let me see if I can go back.

00:42:54.956 --> 00:42:55.710
Or go forward.

00:42:55.710 --> 00:42:58.210
- --so I was just wondering,
if that's something you've seen

00:42:58.210 --> 00:43:01.227
before, what do you
think is going on there?

00:43:01.227 --> 00:43:02.560
Is it simply a coincidence, or--

00:43:02.560 --> 00:43:04.352
- --can you help me
get back to the first--

00:43:04.352 --> 00:43:07.770
anyone can help me
get back to the--

00:43:07.770 --> 00:43:09.490
this corset one.

00:43:09.490 --> 00:43:12.670
Certainly, I noticed it with
the dandy one, the second one.

00:43:12.670 --> 00:43:16.213
And that has to do-- they're
both English caricatures.

00:43:16.213 --> 00:43:18.880
And I think they have to do very
much with the idea of servants.

00:43:18.880 --> 00:43:21.280
Those are servants
lacing you up.

00:43:21.280 --> 00:43:26.530
And so that, I think, is
sort of the main idea--

00:43:26.530 --> 00:43:30.940
and having to do with the idea
that you were an elite person

00:43:30.940 --> 00:43:33.370
because corsetry was
associated not only

00:43:33.370 --> 00:43:37.060
with female sexual beauty,
but also with elite status

00:43:37.060 --> 00:43:41.140
because upper-class people
wore stiffer clothes

00:43:41.140 --> 00:43:43.840
and wore corsets for a
long time before they

00:43:43.840 --> 00:43:46.570
spread to the middle
and working classes.

00:43:46.570 --> 00:43:51.490
So in the Renaissance,
little boys and little girls

00:43:51.490 --> 00:43:52.240
wore corsets--

00:43:52.240 --> 00:43:54.700
because their bodies were
thought to be so weak.

00:43:54.700 --> 00:43:56.860
But as girls grew
up and became women,

00:43:56.860 --> 00:43:59.470
theirs were the bodies that
were marked as still being

00:43:59.470 --> 00:44:01.300
weak and in need of support.

00:44:01.300 --> 00:44:06.040
But this idea that the
supported, tightened body

00:44:06.040 --> 00:44:08.290
was going to be an
elite person's body--

00:44:08.290 --> 00:44:12.520
because a poor person's
body was going to be bent

00:44:12.520 --> 00:44:14.320
and stretched out of shape.

00:44:14.320 --> 00:44:16.390
Not like today so much--
that would be fat,

00:44:16.390 --> 00:44:18.460
although you see that
by the 19th century--

00:44:18.460 --> 00:44:22.990
but that it wouldn't be an
erect, graceful, aristocratic

00:44:22.990 --> 00:44:23.710
body.

00:44:23.710 --> 00:44:26.590
And the corset was supposed
to maintain that for you.

00:44:26.590 --> 00:44:30.073
So I think both of these images
are showing someone who's

00:44:30.073 --> 00:44:31.615
a member of the
elite, and then there

00:44:31.615 --> 00:44:34.780
are servants as well as
colleagues lacing them up.

00:44:34.780 --> 00:44:37.390
This one here-- those
are both servants.

00:44:37.390 --> 00:44:38.730
The one there is black.

00:44:38.730 --> 00:44:40.360
The other one is
probably intended

00:44:40.360 --> 00:44:42.495
to be French or Italian.

00:44:42.495 --> 00:44:45.400
With the comb in his hair,
he's like a [SPEAKING FRENCH]..

00:44:45.400 --> 00:44:48.220
So you've got all these
sort of foreign people

00:44:48.220 --> 00:44:51.740
helping him look more stylish.

00:44:51.740 --> 00:44:55.130
But to be stylish is already
in the British caricature

00:44:55.130 --> 00:44:58.020
being seen as being a
little bit effeminate.

00:45:00.610 --> 00:45:02.260
This is a really
fascinating thing

00:45:02.260 --> 00:45:04.420
because if you
look at literature

00:45:04.420 --> 00:45:06.790
from the early
19th century, there

00:45:06.790 --> 00:45:09.850
are quite a few references
to men wearing corsets.

00:45:09.850 --> 00:45:12.010
In Thackeray-- Vanity Fair--

00:45:12.010 --> 00:45:16.240
that Joseph Sedley,
the fat guy that she's

00:45:16.240 --> 00:45:17.650
flirting with at first--

00:45:17.650 --> 00:45:19.270
he wears a corset at the table.

00:45:19.270 --> 00:45:23.110
And he gets agitated and starts
having difficulty breathing.

00:45:23.110 --> 00:45:26.370
And his father's like,
cut his corset strings.

00:45:26.370 --> 00:45:29.440
Or in Cousin Bette when Baron
Hulot starts having the affair

00:45:29.440 --> 00:45:30.970
with Valérie Marneffe.

00:45:30.970 --> 00:45:33.040
He starts wearing a
corset to look younger

00:45:33.040 --> 00:45:34.600
and thinner and more military.

00:45:34.600 --> 00:45:38.650
So I think that the use
of having people of color

00:45:38.650 --> 00:45:41.830
is to imply I'm the one
who's the employer of all

00:45:41.830 --> 00:45:42.550
of these people.

00:45:42.550 --> 00:45:44.350
I am of a higher social status.

00:45:44.350 --> 00:45:45.316
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:45:45.316 --> 00:45:46.765
- Thanks.

00:45:46.765 --> 00:45:47.731
- Thank you.

00:45:47.731 --> 00:45:48.990
- One more?

00:45:48.990 --> 00:45:49.490
OK.

00:45:49.490 --> 00:45:50.570
Thank you so much.

00:45:50.570 --> 00:45:53.020
[APPLAUSE]

